        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will tune the four spectral windows in 2.0 GHz bandwidth(usable bandwidth of 1.875 GHz), 128-channel dual polarization, TDM mode, with one widow centered at the [CII] line frequency and the other three windows in sidebands observing the continuum. In order to fully resolve the host galaxy of J0100+2802 and study the kinematic of the ISM gas, we request to resolve the line emission over four ALMA beams into three consecutive 100 km/s channels with SNR~10 in each beam. This will also allow us to detect and resolve the continuum emission from the central few kpc starburst region at a SNR~13. This configuration will allow us to measure the velocity map and calculate the dynamical mass traced by [CII] emission line. The representative spectral window resolution is ~36 km/s, which will allow us to measure the profile of the [CII] emission line accurately. We will also serach for line components with large velocity offsets within the whole 3.75 GHz sideband (two consecutive base band windows, coverage of ~4000km/s in velocity).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to carry out ALMA Band 6 observations to map the [CII] line and dust continuum emission toward J0100+2802, the most luminous quasar at z&gt;6. Similar high-redshift quasar host has an average size of ~0.6". In order to fully resolve the emission to measure the host galaxy size and kinematics, we require the C36-6 configuration with resolution of 0.15" (~0.9kpc). This also matches the resolution of our HST/WFC3 near-IR imaging, allowing mapping of star formation and dust obscuration in the quasar host.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to map the [CII] line and dust continuum emission from J0100+2802 at z=6.3. The redshift of [CII] has been accurately determined from our PdBI observations (Delta z ~0.002 or ~80 MHz in frequency at ~260GHz). We will tune the four spectral windows in 2.0 GHz bandwidth (usable badwidth of 1.875 GHz), 128-channel dual polarization, TDM mode, with one window centered at the [CII] line frequency and the other three windows observing the continuum. The [CII] line width detected in our PdBI project is 350 km/s, which can be well covered by the 1.875 GHz window. We will also serach for line components with large velocity offsets within the whole 3.75 GHz sideband (two consecutive baseband windows,coverage of ~4000km/s in velocity.)
The [CII] line and dust continuum detections in J0100+2802 from PdBI indicate line peak flux density of 10 mJy and continuum flux density of 1.4 mJy. Based on these measurements, we estimate the line surface brightness of J0100+2802 to be 1.5 mJy per beam, while the continuum surface brightness is 0.21 mJy per beam. Here we request the sensitivity of 0.25 mJy per beam over 36 km/s bandwidth under a 0.15" angular resolution. This configuration will reach 6 sigma dectection at line peak position and continuum sensitivity of 0.016 mJy per beam (a total bandwidth of 7.5GHz with the three continuum windows is adopted here). The goal is to resolve the line emission over four ALMA beams into three consecutive 100 km/s channels with SNR~10 in each beam. This will also allow us to detect and resolve the continuum emission from the central few kpc starburst region at a SNR~13. The corresponding observing time is about 2.2 hours, including the overheads.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
